\n# CKAD Interactive Learning Units - Module 1: Application Design & Build\n# Units 1-20: Container images, pod design, multi-container patterns, security\n\nputs \"Creating CKAD Module 1 Interactive Learning Units (1-20)...\"\n\n# Find the CKAD course for integration\nckad_course = Course.find_by(title: 'CKAD Certification Prep')\n\n# Unit 1: Understanding Container Images\nInteractiveLearningUnit.create!(\n  title: \"Understanding Container Images\",\n  slug: \"ckad-container-images-basics\",\n  category: \"images\",\n  difficulty: \"easy\",\n  estimated_minutes: 3,\n  xp_reward: 10,\n  \n  concept_explanation: <<~MARKDOWN,\n    # Understanding Container Images\n    \n    Container images are read-only templates that contain everything needed to run an application:\n    - Application code\n    - Runtime environment\n    - System libraries\n    - Dependencies\n    - Configuration files\n    \n    ## Image Components\n    \n    ```\n    Repository:Tag\n    nginx:1.25\n    └─┬──┘ └┬─┘\n      │     └─── Version identifier\n      └───────── Image name\n    ```\n    \n    ## Why Images Matter for CKAD\n    \n    - **Portability**: Run anywhere (dev, test, prod)\n    - **Consistency**: Same environment every time\n    - **Version Control**: Tag different versions\n    - **Efficiency**: Layered architecture saves space\n    \n    Understanding images is foundational for deploying applications in Kubernetes.\n  MARKDOWN\n  \n  learning_objectives: [\n    \"Understand what container images are and their components\",\n    \"List locally stored container images\",\n    \"Identify image repositories, tags, and IDs\"\n  ],\n  \n  prerequisites: [],\n  \n  command_to_learn: \"docker images\",\n  command_variations: [\n    \"docker image ls\",\n    \"docker image list\"\n  ],\n  \n  practice_hints: [\n    \"Start with the 'docker' command\",\n    \"Use the 'images' subcommand to list all images\",\n    \"The complete command is: docker images\"\n  ],\n  \n  quiz_question_text: \"What command lists all container images stored locally on your machine?\",\n  quiz_question_type: \"multiple_choice\",\n  quiz_options: [\n    {\n      text: \"docker list\",\n      correct: false,\n      explanation: \"There is no 'docker list' command. The correct command is 'docker images'.\"\n    },\n    {\n      text: \"docker images\",\n      correct: true,\n      explanation: \"Correct! 'docker images' displays all locally stored images with their repository, tag, image ID, creation time, and size.\"\n    },\n    {\n      text: \"docker ps -a\",\n      correct: false,\n      explanation: \"'docker ps -a' lists containers, not images. Use 'docker images' to list images.\"\n    },\n    {\n      text: \"docker container ls\",\n      correct: false,\n      explanation: \"'docker container ls' lists running containers, not images. Use 'docker images' for images.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \n  scenario_title: \"Inspecting Local Images\",\n  scenario_description: \"You've joined a new team and need to understand what container images are already on the development machine.\",\n  scenario_steps: [\n    {\n      step: 1,\n      instruction: \"List all container images on your system\",\n      command: \"docker images\",\n      explanation: \"This shows all available images with their repository, tag, ID, creation date, and size\",\n      validation: \"You should see columns for REPOSITORY, TAG, IMAGE ID, CREATED, and SIZE\"\n    },\n    {\n      step: 2,\n      instruction: \"Count how many unique images you have\",\n      command: \"docker images | wc -l\",\n      explanation: \"This counts the number of lines in the output (subtract 1 for the header)\",\n      validation: \"You'll get a number representing total images plus one header line\"\n    },\n    {\n      step: 3,\n      instruction: \"List only image IDs\",\n      command: \"docker images -q\",\n      explanation: \"The -q flag shows only the numeric IDs, useful for scripting\",\n      validation: \"You should see only hexadecimal image IDs, one per line\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \n  tags: [\"kubernetes\", \"ckad\", \"docker\", \"images\", \"containers\"]\n)\n\n# Unit 2: Pulling Specific Image Versions\nInteractiveLearningUnit.create!(\n  title: \"Pulling Specific Image Versions\",\n  slug: \"ckad-pulling-image-versions\",\n  category: \"images\",\n  difficulty: \"easy\",\n  estimated_minutes: 4,\n  xp_reward: 10,\n  \n  concept_explanation: <<~MARKDOWN,\n    # Pulling Specific Image Versions\n    \n    When deploying applications, you need to pull container images from registries like Docker Hub.\n    \n    ## Image Tag Syntax\n    \n    ```bash\n    docker pull [REGISTRY/]IMAGE[:TAG]\n    \n    # Examples:\n    docker pull nginx                    # pulls nginx:latest\n    docker pull nginx:1.25              # specific version\n    docker pull docker.io/nginx:1.25    # with explicit registry\n    ```\n    \n    ## Best Practices\n    \n    ✅ **Always specify version tags** in production\n    ❌ **Avoid using `latest`** tag - it's unpredictable\n    \n    ```bash\n    # Good\n    docker pull nginx:1.25.3\n    \n    # Bad (in production)\n    docker pull nginx\n    docker pull nginx:latest\n    ```\n    \n    ## Why Version Pinning Matters\n    \n    - **Reproducibility**: Same image every time\n    - **Debugging**: Know exactly what version is running\n    - **Rollback**: Easy to revert to previous versions\n    - **Security**: Control when updates happen\n  MARKDOWN\n  \n  learning_objectives: [\n    \"Pull container images from Docker Hub\",\n    \"Specify exact image versions using tags\",\n    \"Understand the importance of version pinning\"\n  ],\n  \n  prerequisites: [\"ckad-container-images-basics\"],\n  \n  command_to_learn: \"docker pull nginx:1.25\",\n  command_variations: [\n    \"docker pull nginx:1.25.0\",\n    \"docker image pull nginx:1.25\",\n    \"docker pull docker.io/nginx:1.25\"\n  ],\n  \n  practice_hints: [\n    \"Start with 'docker pull' to download an image\",\n    \"Specify the image name 'nginx' followed by a colon and version\",\n    \"The complete command is: docker pull nginx:1.25\"\n  ],\n  \n  quiz_question_text: \"Why should you specify exact version tags instead of using 'latest' in production?\",\n  quiz_question_type: \"multiple_choice\",\n  quiz_options: [\n    {\n      text: \"It makes downloads faster\",\n      correct: false,\n      explanation: \"Version tags don't affect download speed. The reason is reproducibility and control.\"\n    },\n    {\n      text: \"It ensures reproducible deployments and version control\",\n      correct: true,\n      explanation: \"Correct! Specific tags guarantee you deploy the same version every time, making debugging and rollbacks easier.\"\n    },\n    {\n      text: \"The 'latest' tag doesn't work in Kubernetes\",\n      correct: false,\n      explanation: \"'latest' works in Kubernetes, but it's unpredictable since it changes over time.\"\n    },\n    {\n      text: \"Docker Hub requires version tags\",\n      correct: false,\n      explanation: \"Docker Hub doesn't require version tags, but using them is a best practice.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \n  scenario_title: \"Preparing a Production Deployment\",\n  scenario_description: \"Your team needs to deploy a web application using NGINX 1.25 for consistency across environments.\",\n  scenario_steps: [\n    {\n      step: 1,\n      instruction: \"Pull the specific NGINX version 1.25\",\n      command: \"docker pull nginx:1.25\",\n      explanation: \"This downloads the exact version y